Rating: 4
These are the best crab cakes I have ever made! Both the chili garlic paste and the jalapeno pepper add extraordinary zip, and in combination with the colorful veggies, kept them from being ho-hum. I used soft bread crumbs in the cakes and panko bread crumbs to dredge the crab cakes, so the coating remained crunchy. Thank you, Epicurious, and thanks to all the reviewers for the great tips for adding yet another "fave" from this site to my recipe collection!

Rating: 4
Delicious!!! I agree with previous reviewer who said you don't need 5 cups of breadcrumbs - I used 1 1/2 in the cakes and about 1 1/2 to dredge. I also used an egg ring which made my crab cakes the perfect size and shape! Have also used canned crabmeat when I was in a hurry and it also turned out beautifully.

Rating: 3
These crab cakes were very good - liked the zip added by the chili-garlic sauce and jalapeno. We got fresh claw crab meat from the seafood department - seemed expensive, but made 8 large cakes for around $20 - so really, quite reasonable. The mayo/chili sauce topping was just the ticket! Did not need all the bread crumbs - only put 1 cup in the recipe and maybe had 1 cup to dredge the cakes in. Yum!

Rating: 4
My husband substituted canned salmon for the crab and used 4 tsps sweet thai chili sauce instead of hot chili sauce for the mayonnaise. The substitution was wonderful!!! Great way to have seafood cakes at a lower cost.